    "user_reviews": [
      {
        "text": "I believe that a Ryzen 5 5500 would have performed very nearly as well for my 1080p budget gaming set up; however, I had a motherboard supporting pcie4.0 and a GPU supporting pcie4.0, so didn't want the 5500 that only supports pcie3.0, and I chose this 5600 as the next cheapest suitable option with pcie4.0 support for use with B550M motherboards. It really makes practically nil difference for gaming though, and I'd go for the 5500 if you don't want to spend more than you need and don't have any special need for pcie4.0. This Ryzen 5 5600 is running well since installed about six weeks ago. Using the stock cooler, which seems to work very well - haven't pushed the CPU really hard yet, but temperatures barely getting above 60 degrees, well under its maximum operating temperature; but note that I have a fairly roomy case with 4 x 140mm case fans and only an RX6600 GPU which doesn't generate huge heat either.",
        "user_name": "SteveH15",
        "source": "pbtech.co.nz",
